07570nam a22009855i 9789048554010DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a9789048554010  a(DE-B1597)626004  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aTR530 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a778.66223/eng/2022071800aGabriel Lippmann's Colour Photography :bScience, Media, Museums /ced. by Hanin Hannouch. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (314 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tGabriel Lippmann’s Colour Photography: A Critical Introduction -- tPart I The Science of Colour Photography and the Colour Photography of Science -- t1. How Lippmann Froze Light and Passed It around for Others to Taste -- t2. Lippmann’s Interferential Colour Photography: A Juncture between the Histories of Spectroscopy and Photography -- t3. Colour Under the Microscope: Santiago Ramón y Cajal Does ‘Histology’ on Lippmann Heliochromes -- t4. Lost in Description: The Misunderstanding of Frederic Ives (1856–1937) and the Experiments of His Son Herbert (1882–1953) on Lippmann’s Interference Photography -- tPart II Media History, Aesthetics, and Culture -- t5. Lippmann Photography and the Problems of Media Historiography -- t6. Richard Neuhauss’s Stuffed Parrot: Interferential Colour Photography, Taxidermy, and Projection -- t7. Brilliant! Enthusiasm for the Aesthetic Qualities of Lippmann’s Interferential Photography -- t8. From Maxwell to Mercury: The Cultural History of Gabriel Lippmann’s Colour Photography -- tPart III Contemporary Reception and Future Trajectories -- t9. Materiality, Identification, and Conservation of Lippmann Plates -- t10. Exhibiting Gabriel Lippmann: A Collaborative Challenge -- t11. Modern Lippmann Photog -- t12. “It’s not just a picture, it’s a magical object”: Interview with Contemporary Lippmann Photographer Filipe Alves -- tAfterword: Building Bridges over Standing Waves -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhysicist Gabriel Lippmann’s (1845–1921) photographic process is one of the oldest methods for producing colour photographs. So why do the achievements of this 1908 Nobel laureate remain mostly unknown outside niche circles? Using the centenary of Lippmann’s death as an opportunity to reflect upon his scientific, photographic, and cultural legacy, this book is the first to explore his interferential colour photography. Initially disclosed in 1891, the emergence of this medium is considered here through three shaping forces: science, media, and museums. A group of international scholars reassess Lippmann’s reception in the field of the history of science, where he is most recognised, by going well beyond his circles in France and delving into the complexity of his colour photography as a medium that challenges various historiographies. Moreover, they focus on the interferential plate as a material object in need of both preservation and exhibition, one that continues to fascinate contemporary analogue photographers. This volume allows readers to get to know Lippmann, grasp the interdisciplinary complexity of his colourful work, and ultimately expand his place in the history of photography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aColor photographyxProcessingxHistory. 4aApplied optics. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 4aMedia studies. 4aPhotographic equipment and techniques: general. 4aScience and Technology. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh  aGabriel Lippmann, Colour Photography, Media Archaeology, History of Science, Museum Collections.1 aAlsch